To prevent the spread of COVID-19, Saudi Arabia announced the closure of all schools across the country, the suspension of air and sea travel to nine countries, and the closure of the Shia oil producing region of Katif in the eastern province.

As of the morning of March 9, four new cases had been confirmed in Saudi Arabia, bringing the total to 15. Most of it comes from Cardiff.

The Saudi Ministry of Education announced Monday that all public and private schools in the country would be closed from Monday until further notice, Al Arabiya News and Gulf News reported Monday.

During the suspension period, the school may take the remote instruction or the network instruction. Education in mosques and study of the Koran throughout the country were suspended except in schools, and the Saudi Games, the country's biggest sporting event, was postponed.

Four new cases were confirmed in Saudi Arabia on Monday morning. Two of them were Bahraini citizens who stopped in Saudi Arabia on their way back from Iraq; one was a United States citizen who had been to the Philippines and Italy before arriving in Saudi Arabia; and the other was a Saudi citizen who had come into contact with the confirmed case of al-qatif.

All of the 11 confirmed cases in Saudi Arabia had previously been in Cardiff. Saudi Arabia on Sunday announced a blockade of the Katif area to prevent the spread of the disease.

According to the Saudi Ministry of the Interior, Katif will not allow access, but the current stay out of Katif residents can still return.

All local government and private institutions, companies and shops will be closed, with the exception of pharmacies, hospitals, gas stations, security services and others providing essential services and security.

Vehicles carrying goods and supplies are allowed into Kattev, but they are subject to strict checks.

According to the Al Jazeera, local residents said concrete barricades had been set up on the main road into and out of Kattev, while residents lined up to buy necessities before the supermarket closed. Industry sources predict that the closure of Katif will not affect Saudi oil production.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
At a supermarket in Cardiff. Image: Twitter

Katif is a Shiite stronghold of about 500,000 people in eastern Saudi Arabia. Saudi Arabia is dominated by Sunnis, with less than 15% of Shiites.

More than of his confirmed patients have traveled to Iran. Iran is home to many Shiite holy places and is a popular destination for Shiite pilgrims.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The Red Dot is Cardiff. Image credit: Google maps

Because of the dispute between Saudi Arabia and Iran, Saudi citizens who have visited Iran do not voluntarily report to the authorities, and the Iranian authorities do not stamp the passports of Saudi citizens who have entered the country. Iran has become the eye of the storm in the Middle East. As of August 8, Iran confirmed a total of 6566 cases, the cumulative death of 194 cases.

Saudi Arabia has banned its citizens from traveling to Iran and last week condemned Iran for continuing to allow its citizens to enter the country. Iranian officials and the population of Cardiff had previously complained that the Saudi government discriminated against Shiites.

In addition to Iran, Saudi authorities on Monday banned citizens and residents from traveling to the United Arab Emirates, Kuwait, Bahrain, Lebanon, Syria, Egypt, Iraq, Italy and South Korea.

Persons returning from or having visited the nine countries in the past 14 days will be prohibited from entering Saudi Arabia. On Saturday, Saudi Arabia announced a suspension of overland travel to Bahrain, the United Arab Emirates and Kuwait.

Earlier, Saudi Arabia has announced a full suspension of the small Hajj pilgrimage to Mecca, to prohibit foreign pilgrims to Mecca and Medina.

In addition to the Saudis, the number of confirmed cases in the Gulf states continues to rise.

As of Sunday, three new cases had been confirmed in Qatar, bringing the total to 15. The country announced on Monday that it would suspend passengers from 14 countries.

Bahrain, where 85 cases have been confirmed, has announced that spectators will not be allowed to attend this month's Formula One race. Kuwait, which has 64 confirmed cases, has announced that it has allocated $33 million to fight the disease.
